{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627559"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:49:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17126"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17126","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17126"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.08,0.02,0.75,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9816"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68641"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9816"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17126"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5028"},{"type":"tags","id":"5035"},{"type":"tags","id":"9882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22994"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23019"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68641","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68641"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe hypertension. She is commenced on an intravenous sodium nitroprusside infusion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism of action of sodium nitroprusside?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activates potassium channels in vascular smooth muscle","Inhibits angiotensin converting enzyme","Blocks alpha-adrenergic receptors","Releases nitric oxide causing smooth muscle relaxation","Blocks calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ESodium nitroprusside works by \u003Cstrong\u003Ereleasing nitric oxide\u003C/strong\u003E, which activates guanylate cyclase in vascular smooth muscle cells. This leads to increased cyclic guanosine monophosphate (cGMP) levels, causing smooth muscle relaxation and vasodilation.\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivating potassium channels in vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of action of potassium channel openers such as minoxidil.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting angiotensin converting enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E is how medications like enalapril work to reduce blood pressure.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking alpha-adrenergic receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism seen with alpha blockers such as prazosin.\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is how calcium channel blockers like nifedipine reduce blood pressure.\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E    \u003Cp\u003ENitroprusside causes both arterial and venous dilation, reducing both afterload and preload. A significant concern with its use is that it is metabolised to cyanide, which can accumulate during prolonged administration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sodium nitroprusside is metabolised to release nitric oxide which causes smooth muscle relaxation and vasodilation.","Cyanide is a toxic metabolite of nitroprusside that can accumulate during prolonged administration.","Nitroprusside causes both arterial and venous dilation, reducing both preload and afterload."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17126"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-10T08:59:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-10T09:01:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9816"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68641"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"d